48 /**
49 * Represents a Rule on a Subscription that is used to filter the incoming message from the
50 * Subscription.
51 */
52 export interface RuleDescription {
53 /**
54 * Filter expression used to match messages. Supports 2 types:
55 * - `string`: SQL-like condition expression that is evaluated against the messages'
56 * user-defined properties and system properties. All system properties will be prefixed with
57 * `sys.` in the condition expression.
58 * - `CorrelationFilter`: Properties of the filter will be used to match with the message properties.
59 */
60 filter?: string | CorrelationFilter;
61 /**
62 * Action to perform if the message satisfies the filtering expression.
63 */
64 action?: string;
65 /**
66 * Represents the name of the rule.
67 */
68 name: string;
69 }
70
71 /**
72 * Represents the correlation filter expression.
73 * A CorrelationFilter holds a set of conditions that are matched against user and system properties
74 * of incoming messages from a Subscription.
75 */
76 export interface CorrelationFilter {
77 /**
78 * Value to be matched with the `correlationId` property of the incoming message.
79 */
80 correlationId?: string;
81 /**
82 * Value to be matched with the `messageId` property of the incoming message.
83 */
84 messageId?: string;
85 /**
86 * Value to be matched with the `to` property of the incoming message.
87 */
88 to?: string;
89 /**
90 * Value to be matched with the `replyTo` property of the incoming message.
91 */
92 replyTo?: string;
93 /**
94 * Value to be matched with the `label` property of the incoming message.
95 */
96 label?: string;
97 /**
98 * Value to be matched with the `sessionId` property of the incoming message.
99 */
100 sessionId?: string;
101 /**
102 * Value to be matched with the `replyToSessionId` property of the incoming message.
103 */
104 replyToSessionId?: string;
105 /**
106 * Value to be matched with the `contentType` property of the incoming message.
107 */
108 contentType?: string;
109 /**
110 * Value to be matched with the user properties of the incoming message.
111 */
112 userProperties?: any;
113 }

240 * also fetch even Deferred messages (but not Deadlettered message).

378 /**

380 * @class ReceivedSBMessage

526 * from a Queue/Subscription.

528 * `newMessageWaitTimeoutInSeconds` in the options to provide a timeout.

530 * @param onMessage - Handler for processing each incoming message.
531 * @param onError - Handler for any error that occurs while receiving or processing messages.
532 * @param options - Options to control whether messages should be automatically completed. You can
533 * also provide a timeout in seconds to denote the amount of time to wait for a new message
534 * before closing the receiver.

558 if (this.newMessageWaitTimeoutInSeconds) {

562 `any messages in the last ${

568 // The session manager will not forward this error to user.
569 // Instead, this is taken as a indicator to create a new session client for the next session.
570 const error = translate({

572 description: msg

574 this._notifyError(translate(error));

577 }, this.newMessageWaitTimeoutInSeconds * 1000);

584 // cannot settle the message.

623 if (
624 !bMessage.delivery.remote_settled &&
625 this.receiveMode === ReceiveMode.peekLock &&
626 this.isOpen() // only try to abandon the messages if the connection is still open
627 ) {
628 try {
629 log.error(
630 "[%s] Abandoning the message with id '%s' on the receiver '%s' since " +
631 "an error occured: %O.",
632 connectionId,
633 bMessage.messageId,
634 this.name,

636 );
637 await bMessage.abandon();
638 } catch (abandonError) {
639 const translatedError = translate(abandonError);
640 log.error(

642 "receiver '%s': %O.",
643 connectionId,
644 bMessage.messageId,
645 this.name,
646 translatedError
647 );
648 this._notifyError(translatedError);
649 }
650 }
651 return;
652 } finally {
653 if (this._receiver) {
654 this._receiver!.addCredit(1);
655 }
656 }
657
658 // If we've made it this far, then user's message handler completed fine. Let us try
659 // completing the message.
660 if (
